{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491458","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491458"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:47:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"944"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/944"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.35,0.02,0.03,0.18,0.42]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51673"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"944","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/944"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"944"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36972"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"331"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1248"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11335"},{"type":"contributions","id":"11345"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14855"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34611"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51673"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents to his general practitioner after experiencing a sudden onset episode of confusion and disorientation. This occurred about two hours after a dinner party to celebrate his birthday, when he stood up to grab a drink of water. He felt very unwell and his friends helped him to sit down. He was sweating profusedly but began to feel better after a drink of cordial.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUpon questioning, he has never had anything like this before. He did have some nausea this morning and did not feel like eating his breakfast or taking his morning medication at the time. The symptoms resolved a few hours later and he was able to eat a normal meal by lunchtime. He has not had any diarrhoea or vomiting or fever in the last week.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history includes newly diagnosed hypertension two weeks ago and a Roux-en-Y gastric bypass for morbid obesity three months ago. Since the surgery he has managed to lose 30 kg, with his BMI dropping from 44 to 31. He is currently on hydrochlorothiazide 25mg and bisoprolol 5mg daily.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely explanation for his symptoms?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Postprandial hypoglycaemia","Dehydration","Reactive hypovolaemia","Orthostatic hypotension secondary to medication","Early dumping syndrome"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EWhilst there could be several reasons for this episode, with a rapid response to a drink of cordial the clinical picture fits well for \u003Cstrong\u003Epost-prandial hypoglycaemia \u003C/strong\u003E(late dumping syndrome). Dumping is a well-recognised sequela of gastric bypass surgery. In this type of surgery, apart from the presence of a very small gastric pouch, food materials can be moved very rapidly in an uncoordinated manner into the small intestine. There are two components to dumping, the first occurring within a short time after eating, with a sudden and rapid fluid shift into the gut leading to a transient hypovolaemia (\u003Cstrong\u003Eearly dumping syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E). The time frame does not fit with this patient.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe second phase of dumping may occur several hours after a meal (particularly one rich in carbohydrate) where a rapid and uncoordinated absorption of sugars into the circulation leads to an insulin over-swing and \u003Cstrong\u003Epostprandial hypoglycaemia \u003C/strong\u003E(late dumping syndrome). This likely diagnosis is supported by the observation that the patient\u0027s symptoms settled in response to an oral sugar drink.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough it is certainly possible that this is a case of \u003Cstrong\u003Eorthostatic hypotension secondary to medication\u003C/strong\u003E after newly started medications; the patient\u0027s report of missing his antihypertensives today makes this much less likely. Despite having not eaten breakfast, the patient has had a normal meal at lunchtime and dinner, with no reports of any GI loss such as vomiting or diarrhoea which makes \u003Cstrong\u003Edehydration\u003C/strong\u003E unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Dumping is a very common sequela to the Roux-en-Y procedure."],"references":["Berg P, McCallum R. Dumping Syndrome: A Review of the Current Concepts of Pathophysiology, Diagnosis, and Treatment. Dig Dis Sci 2016; 61:11-18. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/26396002/","Hui, Channing, Aayush Dhakal, and Gustavo J. Bauza. \u0022Dumping syndrome.\u0022 In StatPearls [Internet]. StatPearls Publishing, 2023. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470542/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36972"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"944"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"36972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/36972"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-27T20:52:11+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-27T20:52:57+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"944"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51673"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2